🐧 1. BASIC LINUX COMMANDS (CO1)
pwd → shows current working directory
ls → lists files and directories
ls -l → shows detailed file information
ls -a → displays hidden files
cd dir → changes directory
cd .. → moves to parent directory
mkdir dir → creates a new directory
rmdir dir → removes empty directory
touch file → creates an empty file
cat file → displays file content
nano file → opens file editor
cp f1 f2 → copies file
mv f1 f2 → moves or renames file
rm file → deletes file
clear → clears terminal screen
whoami → shows current user
who → shows logged-in users
date → displays current date/time
cal → shows calendar
man cmd → shows manual of command
⚙️ 2. PROCESS MANAGEMENT COMMANDS (CO1)
ps → displays running processes
ps aux → shows all processes with details
top → monitors processes in real-time
htop → advanced process viewer (interactive)
tree → displays directory structure in tree form
kill PID → terminates a process by ID
kill -9 PID → forcefully kills a process
killall name → kills all processes by name
jobs → shows background jobs
bg → resumes job in background
fg → brings job to foreground
command & → runs process in background
nice → starts process with priority
renice → changes priority of running process
👨‍👦 3. PROCESS CREATION (CO1)
gcc file.c → compiles C program
./a.out → executes compiled program
⏱️ 4. FCFS SCHEDULING (CO2)
gcc fcfs.c → compiles FCFS program
./a.out → runs FCFS scheduling
⚡ 5. SJF SCHEDULING (CO2)
gcc sjf.c → compiles SJF program
./a.out → runs SJF scheduling
🧠 6. PRIORITY SCHEDULING (CO2)
gcc priority.c → compiles priority scheduling
./a.out → executes priority scheduling
🔒 7. BANKER’S ALGORITHM (CO3)
gcc banker.c → compiles banker’s algorithm
./a.out → runs deadlock detection
📄 8. FIFO PAGE REPLACEMENT (CO4)
gcc fifo.c → compiles FIFO program
./a.out → executes page replacement
🐚 9. SHELL COMMANDS & SCRIPT (CO5)
echo → prints output to terminal
read var → takes user input
exit → exits shell
expr → performs arithmetic operations
$(( )) → evaluates arithmetic expression
-f file → checks if file exists
-d dir → checks if directory exists
-r file → checks read permission
-w file → checks write permission
nano script.sh → creates shell script
chmod +x script.sh → gives execute permission
./script.sh → runs shell script
🔀 10. IF-ELSE SHELL SCRIPT (CO5)
if → checks condition
then → executes block if true
else → executes block if false
fi → ends if block
-eq → equal comparison
-ne → not equal
-gt → greater than
-lt → less than
-ge → greater or equal
-le → less or equal
= → string equal
!= → string not equal
